description:
In lichen_l2.c lines 510-516 (non-LICHEN_LINK path):

    if (len > sizeof(rx_ipv6_buf)) {
        LOG_WRN("Packet too large: %zu", len);
        k_mutex_unlock(&rx_mutex);
        return;
    }
    memcpy(rx_ipv6_buf, data, len);

rx_ipv6_buf is sized as LICHEN_L2_MTU + IPV6_BASE_HDR_LEN = 200 + 40 = 240 bytes.

The LoRa RX buffer in lora_l2.c is 256 bytes (line 142). A malformed/hostile packet of 241-255 bytes would pass lora_recv but be rejected here with a warning.

This is correct defensive coding - the bounds check prevents buffer overflow. However, the LOG_WRN message could be more informative about the actual limit (240 bytes) for debugging.

This is informational - no actual bug, just noting the implicit size dependency between LICHEN_L2_MTU + IPV6_BASE_HDR_LEN (240) and MAX_LORA_FRAME (255).

**NOT A BUG** - marking as closed, filed for documentation only.
